subSubSection.paragraph: Type-material. The holotype ♀ , from Port Elliot ( SA ), is in ANIC and has been examined in the course of this revision. It is in excellent condition. It is labelled as type by Malloch.

Diagnosis. This species, together with
L. assimilis
and
L. weschei
, differs from other Australian
Lispe
by the slight forward curvature of vein M towards vein R4+5 ( Fig. 306 ).
L. xenochaeta
differs from both
L. assimilis
and
L. weschei
by the presence of a strong submedian v seta on mid tibia.

Vikhrev (2014: 168) gives locality data for specimens he collected in New South Wales , South Australia and Victoria .

Thorax . Ground-colour black. Scutum and scutellum generally yellowish-grey dusted, sometimes very much more grey, sometimes very much more yellow or yellowish-brown; pleura more grey. Scutum with weakly marked but distinct brown vittae as follows: a median vitta running from neck to scutellum and sometimes encroaching weakly on to scutellum, and a pair of narrow vittae along the line of the dc setae, these sometimes reduced to enlarged and partially confluent bristle-dots in ♀ ; also with thinly dusted dark markings as follows: a thin prst vitta just mesad of dc , running from neck to a short distance behind suture, a broad prst patch over ia and sa , and a post vitta between dc and ia , these often less conspicuous in ♀ . Anterior spiracle yellowish. Acr setulae in 5 irregular rows at suture. Dc 2+4, all setae usually long and strong, sometimes anterior 2 post pairs rather reduced. 2 pprn . 1+2 ia , all long and strong. 1+1 sa , both strong. 1 strong and 1 weaker proepisternal setae. 1 strong proepimeral, equal to the strong proepisternal, with 2–3, rarely up to 9, adjacent setulae. Anepisternum with 1 short seta in upper anterior corner; posterior row with 3 strong and 3 weak setae. 3 strong kepst , lower one closer to posterior than to anterior seta. Meron bare, rarely with a setula above hind coxa. Scutellum with disc densely setulose, with 1 row of setulae descending on to sides; ventral surface bare.

FIGURES 326–327 .
Lispe xenochaeta Malloch
, ♂. 326 . Abdomen, dorsal view. 327 . Sternites 1–5. (WA. Junana Rock.)

subSubSection.paragraph: Legs . Coxae, trochanters, femora and tarsi black, femora broadly yellow at apex; tibiae yellow. Fore coxa bare behind. Fore femur without av setae or spinules; pv row complete, but the setae sparse and mostly shorter than femoral depth; pd row complete. Fore tibia with 1 short submedian pv seta, without ad ; with d , pd and 0 ( ♂ ) or 1 ( ♀ ) short pv apical setae. Fore tarsomeres without modifications. Mid femur with only short setulae on av and pv surfaces, except for a few short fine pv setae in basal third in ♂ , equal to femoral depth; 1 a at middle; 2 p preapicals. Mid tibia with 1 submedian p and 1 strong v also at middle; with strong ad , av , pv and v apicals, and a weaker p apical. Mid tarsomeres without modifications. Hind coxa without a seta on posterior apical margin. Hind trochanter only short-setulose below. Hind femur with 1 strong av and, in ♂ , with 2–3 fine pv in basal third, the pv longer than femoral depth, and with 1 each short av and pv preapicals, otherwise with only setulae on ventral surfaces; ad row complete; 1 pd preapical. Hind tibia with 1 ad , 1 av , and 1 pd ; d and ad preapical setae present; 1 av but no pv apical. Hind tarsomeres not modified.

Wing . Clear. Tegula brown to orange, basicosta yellow. Crossvein r-m placed below the point where vein R1 enters costa; dm-cu straight, longer than apical section of vein CuA1. Vein M slightly curved forward before apex and converging with vein R4+5 (as in
L. assimilis
, Fig. 306 ). Calypters white, with creamy margins. Haltere yellow.

Abdomen . Ground-colour black. Dust on tergites grey, sometimes partly tinged with yellow, especially behind. In ♂ , dorsal areas of tergites with a pattern of large dark quadrate spots ( Fig. 326 ), these spots mostly coalescing on tergites 3 and 4 and completely coalescing on tergite 5, not encroaching far on to sides of tergites (as in
L. assimilis
, Fig. 308 ); in ♀ , this dark pattern slightly less extensive, the dark spots on tergites 3 and 4 not coalescing, separated by dust (as in
L. assimilis
♂ , Fig. 307 ), and the mark on tergite 5 with a dusted indentation on hind-margin. ♂ epandrium very large, mainly grey dusted; ♀ ovipositor with exposed tergites dusted grey to brownish-grey. Sternites 1–5 grey dusted; sternites 3 and 4 subshining in ♂ . Setae weakly developed, the only erect setae being a pair of lateral marginals on tergite 4 and 3 pairs of marginals on tergite 5. Sternite 2 with a pair of strong setae, ♂ sternites 3–5 greatly expanded and sternites 3 and 4 completely covered with short dense setulae ( Fig. 327 ), sternites 3–5 in ♀ with only sparse setulae.

FIGURES 328–329 .
Lispe xenochaeta Malloch
, ♂. 328 . Cercal plate, lateral view, with part of epandrium. 329 . Cercal plate, dorsal view. (NT, Todd River.)

FIGURE 330 .
Lispe xenochaeta Malloch
, ♂ phallic complex, lateral view. (V, Tatyoon.)

subSubSection.paragraph:
♀ ovipositor
( Figs 331–333 ). Tergites 6 and 7 complete; tergite 8 divided dorsally, each half displaced laterally by the large epiproct. Sternite 6 absent; what appears to be sternite 7 represented by a curious branched plate; sternite 8 represented by 2 small, narrow, weakly sclerotised plates. Epiproct large, with several setae. Hypoproct large, with only weak spines at apex. Cercus broad, plate-like, connected to the epiproct, with several strong setae. 3 spermathecae.
Measurements . Wing-length, 4.5–5.5 mm ( ♂ ), 5.0– 6.5 mm ( ♀ ). Body-length, 6.0–7.0 mm ( ♂ ), 6.5–8.0 mm ( ♀ ).
Biology. Nothing known. Adults have been found in a variety of inland and coastal habitats.
Distribution. Known only from Australia (WA, NT, Q, NSW, ACT, V, SA).
